{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"67d408c1-d7c5-4c9f-b867-08312f69f533","content":"Here's my analysis of evaluation performance issues in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n---\n\n### 🔴 Issue 1: File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n**Problem:** `System.IO.File::ReadAllText` performs disk I/O during evaluation. Property functions run synchronously and block the evaluation phase. This is one of the most expensive patterns possible.\n\n**Fix:** Move file reading to a target at build time, or use a custom task that runs during execution, not evaluation.\n\n---\n\n### 🟠 Issue 2: Overly Broad Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n**Problem:** `**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree at evaluation time. As the repo grows (adding tools, packages, data, etc.), this becomes increasingly expensive. Only `bin`/`obj` are excluded — directories like `.git`, `node_modules`, or test data will be crawled.\n\n**Fix:** Narrow the glob to specific file types (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes` so the SDK's glob cache can skip them.\n\n---\n\n### 🟡 Issue 3: Chained Import Depth (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\n**Problem:** Each nested `<Import>` adds to the import chain depth. At 3 levels this is minor, but this pattern tends to grow. Deep chains (>20) measurably slow evaluation. Additionally, these imports are outside the SDK import sandwich, placed after SDK props/targets have already loaded.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Issue | Severity | Impact |\n|---|---|---|\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | High | Blocks evaluation with disk I/O |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Medium | Walks entire directory tree every evaluation |\n| 3-level import chain | Low | Additive cost, scaling risk |\n\nThe **file I/O property function** is the most impactful issue to fix first.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"05a49a9b-1809-469e-acc6-135ab807dbd7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues in this project.\n\nThe issues I can identify:\n\n1. **File I/O property function during evaluation** (line 13): `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` - This reads a file during project evaluation, which is expensive. Property functions with file I/O block the evaluation phase.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern** (line 9): `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` - This is a very broad glob that walks the entire directory tree. If the project directory grows (e.g., node_modules, .git, large data directories), this becomes very expensive during evaluation.\n\n\n3. **Nested import hierarchy** (lines 6, spanning three levels): The chain of imports adds evaluation overhead at each level, and while three levels isn't inherently problematic, this pattern could easily expand and compound the performance impact.","outputTokens":795,"requestId":"1C00:1300AE:2728A3:2E77AD:69E82072"},"id":"bb402798-7ee3-4d18-a1de-8331c479070a","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:12:38.140Z","parentId":"03335b54-b2c1-4d3f-9b90-7117caa95db7"}
